Kaggle Housing Sale Price Prediction
¶

Name: YANFANG GUO
E-mail:yanfang.guo@vub.be
Master of Applied Computer Science,VUB

Abstract
¶

The housing Sale prices problem is a regression problem. It contains 79 features which describe the quality and quantity of the property. Machine learning algorithms are applied to this supervised regression problem. Here I use the filter and wrapper method together to select the features. First use the correlation between the feature and Sale Price to filter some really uncorrelated features, then use the wrapper method to select the features. Three models includes simple linear regression, LASSO, and SVM are selected to predict the price. Finally, to increse the robustness of the model, I use the random subspace and bagging methods to combine the models together. The best score in Kaggle is 0.12747.

Introduction
¶

Dataset Description¶

The dataset is from Kaggle housing price,There is a train and a test file.This dataset contains 79 features which are related when sell houses.79 variables focus on the quality and quantity of many physical attributes of the property. Most of the variables are exactly the type of information that a typical home buyer would want to know about a potential property.The trainset contains 1460 variables while the test dataset contains 1459 variables. This dataset contains both category attributes and numeric attritubes. Among 79 features, "Alley', 'PoolQC', 'Fence' and 'MiscVal'" have more than half of the missing values,and for numeric features, "MasVnrArea", "BsmtFinSF2", "X2ndFlrSF", "LowQualFinSF", "BsmtFullBath", "BsmtHalfBath", "HalfBath", "EnclosedPorch", "X3SsnPorch", "ScreenPorch" contains more than half of the 0.(more details will dissicused in the data preprocessing section).

FillNa¶

Here I write a function fillNa to fill all NA's. It works like this:

1. stored all no Na in a vector
2. for missing values, random select a value using runif() in vector.
In [3]:
# fillNa
fillNa <- function(x) {
  noNa <- x[!is.na(x)]
  for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    if (is.na(x[i])) {
      index = round(runif(1, min = 1, max = length(noNa)))
      x[i] <- noNa[index]
    }
  }
  return (x)
}

# fill all NA
for (i in seq(length(train))) {
  train[[i]] <- fillNa(train[[i]])
}

is.goodAttr <- function(x) {
  print(cor(as.numeric(x), price))
  plot(x, price)
  hist(as.numeric(x))
}
lm_test_attr <- function(testMat) {
  t.lm <- lm(price ~ ., testMat)
  index <- sample(1:nrow(testMat), round(0.5 * nrow(testMat)))
  print(summary(t.lm))
  pr.lm <- predict(t.lm, testMat[-index,])
  error.lm <-
    sqrt(sum((testMat[-index, length(testMat)] - pr.lm) ^ 2) / length(pr.lm))
  return(error.lm)
}

Model Selection Analyse¶

Our Trainset now contains 43 features,the size is 1460 which is not a very large dataSet and it is the Regression Problem, So a among all the Machine Learning Algorithms, I will Choose Linear Regression Model, SVM, LASSO.

Model 1: Linear Regression¶

The simplest model for linear regression is one that involves a linear combination of input variables. $$ y(\mathbf{x,w}) = w_0 + w_1x_1 + \cdots + w_Dx_D $$ And $\mathbf x = (x_1,\dots,x_D)^\top$，This is the Linear Regression

svm model¶

support vector machines are supervised learning models with associated learning algorithms that analyze data used for classification and regression analysis. It is characterized by usage of kernels, absence of local minima, sparseness of the solution and capacity control obtained by acting on the margin, or on number of support vectors, etc.

SVM can be used to avoid difficulties of using linear functions in the high dimensional feature space and optimization problem is transformed into dual convex quadratic programmes. In regression case the loss function is used to penalize errors that are grater than threshold - . Such loss functions usually lead to the sparse representation of the decision rule, giving significant algorithmic and representational advantages.

Tuning Parameters in SVM models¶

One Difficulty I find in SVM is to find the right parameters.Here I use the tune()functions in R package{e1071}. It cost a lot of time when tuning the SVM models, so here I use greedy techique.

  1. First I setranges=list(cost=10^(-1:2)) to tune the cost,
  2. use the optimal cost to tune the epsilon,setranges=list(epsilon=10^(-1:2), to find the best epsilon.
  3. Later tune the SVM again in smaller ranges.

Lasso Model¶

In statistics and machine learning, lasso (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator) is a regression analysis method that performs both variable selection and regularization in order to enhance the prediction accuracy and interpretability of the statistical model it produces.

For Linear Regression,we have $$ y(\mathbf{x,w}) = \sum_{j=0}^{M-1} w_j \phi_j(\mathbf x) = \mathbf{w^\top \phi(x)} $$ where the sum-of-squares error function is deﬁned by $$ E_D(\mathbf w) = \frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=1}^N \{t_n-\mathbf w^\top\mathbf \phi(\mathbf x_n)\}^2 $$

We could use Maximum likelihood and least squares to understand our linear regression problems. So at last,we use this formula. $$ \frac{1}{2}\sum_{n=1}^N \{t_n-\mathbf w^\top\mathbf \phi(\mathbf x_n)\}^2 + \frac \lambda 2 \sum_{j=1}^M |w_j|^q $$

When $q=1$, we called it Lasso. When $\lambda$ is larger enough, some $w_j=0$ which makes our model sparse. LASSO does both parameter shrinkage and variable selection automatically

Before using Lasso, I transform all the category attributes in to dummy variables.(Lasso do not support factor variables)

library(lars)
price<-train$SalePrice

Ensemble Techniques

Random Subspace¶

Here I find the linear regression is fast, so I will train linear model several times and select the best to make it more robust. The steps of train linear regression model.

In [24]:
# initialize SalePrice and error
SalePrice<-cbind(rep(0,1459))
error<-c(1)
train<-train.lm
test<-test.lm

for(i in names(test)){
  test[[i]]<-as.numeric(test[[i]])
}
for(i in names(train)){
  train[[i]]<-as.numeric(train[[i]])
}

# repeat the training step for 30 times
for (i in runif(30,0.85,0.95)){
    
    # random sampling
  index1<-sample(1:nrow(train),round(i*nrow(train)))
     #train model
  t.lm<-lm(SalePrice ~ .,train[index1,])
    #cross validation
  pr.lm<-predict(t.lm,train[-index1,])
    
  error.lm<- sqrt(sum((train$SalePrice[-index1]-pr.lm)^2)/length(pr.lm))
  error<-c(error,error.lm)
    # predict results
  test.lm<-predict(t.lm,test)
  test.lm<-exp(test.lm)
  SalePrice<-cbind(SalePrice,test.lm)
}

# only Select the error rate<0.15 predicted results
temp<-which(error<0.15)
price<-SalePrice[,temp]
# The Final result is the meal value of SalePrice
SalePrice<-apply(SalePrice,1,mean)
#write.csv(cbind(Id,SalePrice),file = "lm1.csv")

Discussion and Conclusion
¶

Final Kaggle Score¶

Problems¶

The Kaggle housing price prediction is a real example in Ames,Iowa. This competition both predict the housing price and help me apply the technique I learned during the Machine learning class. During this competition I learn a lot and also had deeper understanding about Machine learning algorithms, especially the feature selection, and the bagging technique. But there are still doubts that puzzeled me.

  • How to deal with outliers?
    In the data cleaning procedure, I tried to remove all the SalePrices outliers, which include SalePrice more than 4.5e5, but I do not know why the error is greater than removed before.
  • Why does random feature does not work?
    In ensembling models part, I also tried to randomly select features to train the model, then select the the model with best performance(Like randomForest), but the prediction is really poor, it is not as good as selecting features artificially.

Conclusion¶

  • The feature selection is very important. I tried to give the prediction using multiple different feature subset, and later I found a good feature selection is very important.
  • The Model Selection is also very important. Cause I also tried to use rpart ,tree and nnet to predict, which gave very bad prediction.
  • Visualzing data can give a direct hint about how to dealing with the data.
  • Sometimes do not make the problems complicated, some naive solutions and models can also give a good result.
